author: @maramac42
text:
If HYBE and ADOR are SO cruel, and apparently vindictive, toward NewJeans, please tell me...

Why did they support and allow them to perform throughout the HYBE building? 
Why did they furnish those same rooms, including BTS's practice room, for that purpose? 
Why did they organise and close off those rooms for filming? A huge task.
Why did they supply, clothe, rehearse and pay the backup dancers? (No, they didn't just wander in off the street...)
Why did they supply a planner, choreographer, film crew and staff team? Did that include clothing and... make-up??? ğŸ˜²
(Notice I'm not including the whole structure around the actual KGMA Awards - supported and supplied by HYBE and ADOR.) 

*And why didn't NewJeans JUST SAY NO to the whole thing - like the whining, overprivileged, complaining, disrespectful, ungrateful young millionaires that they are?* 

I think that those are fair questions. Hmm?


Here's one more... Will these five *glowering puppets* one day, when they've emotionally matured, look back and realise their truly bad decisions? 
Will they realize how they were used?
The only puppet strings attached to NaiveJeans are being pulled by the self-seeking Ms Min Hee-Jin. 
And please don't say that it's for the love of "Bunnies". It's actually burning ambition, but MHJ will soon douse that flame!

text:
NJSâ€™s music has always carried a sense of melancholy, even in its most cheerful moments. It feels like a present continuous tense, yet at the same time, like a past perfect tense. This remix, in particular, feels like itâ€™s gently narrating to usâ€”revisiting a story that has long been settled, while slowly unfolding a new present continuous chapter.

To me, NJS is truly the utopia of K-pop. Before their debut, I never realized that a groupâ€™s work could heal peopleâ€™s hearts so profoundly. Just seeing them naturally brings warmth to my heart. Whether in terms of music or emotions, NewJeans embodies my original love and aspirations for K-pop. Their presence has made me realize that truly great works have the power to heal and bring warmth to the soul.
